


<p>
  In a previous section,
  we looked at problems when an object is thrown directly upward
  and then lands in exactly the same spot it was thrown from.
  Of course, frequenlty, when an object is thrown directly upward,
  it does not land in precisely the same spot it was thrown
  at but at a different height.
  For example, if a person who is six feet tall throws something upward
  but then doesn't catch it, it lands six feet below where it started.
  Or an object could land on a roof or ledge.
  (It might not be moving perfectly vertically, but it is close enough!)
</p>


<p>
  To solve problems like this, you will need to enter a different value
  for vertical displacement \( \Delta y \).
  In order to determine the total time an object is in the air,
  you will need to use the quadratic equation.
</p>

<p>
  To use the quadratic equation,
  you must manipulate a formula until it is in the form
  $$
  0 = a \left( \Delta t \right)^2 + b \Delta t + c
  $$
  This equation has two solutions for \( \Delta t \),
  and they are given by the equation
  $$
  \Delta t = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4 a c}}{2 a}
  $$
</p>


<ol class = 'questionList'>
  <li class = 'question'>
    A person throws a ball directly up into the air with a speed of 28 m/s.
    It travels up, reaches the top, falls back down,
    and lands on a ledge that is 15 meters above where it was thrown.
    For how long was the ball in the air?
  </li>
  <li class = 'question'>
    A person throws a ball directly up into the air with a speed of 13 m/s.
    It travels up, reaches the top, falls back down,
    and lands on a ledge that is 4 meters above where it was thrown.
    For how long was the ball in the air?
  </li>
</ol>

<h5>
  What the two solutions mean:
</h5>

<p>
  When you solve a quadratic equation, you will (almost)
  always get two solutions to the problem.
  Sometimes, both are positive,
  but for the two problems above, one of the solutions is negative.
  What does that mean?
</p>

<p>
  For these two problems,
  there are two positive solutions.
  The first solution is when the ball passed the ledge on its way up,
  and the second solution is when it landed on the ledge on its way down.
</p>

<p>
  For example, imagine your solutions are \( \Delta t = 2 \text{ s} \)
  and \( \Delta t = 6 \text{ s} \).
  The person threw the ball, and after two seconds, it was at the point of the ledge.
  The ball continued upward, reached the top of its motion, and started falling back down.
  Four seconds later (6 seconds after it was thrown), it came back to the ledge
  and landed there.
</p>

<p>
  Both of these solutions exist because they are both solutions to the equation.
  They are both times for which the vertical displacement is the height of the ledge.
  However, the question asks specifically for the time before the ball lands on the ledge,
  which means that the second of the two solutions is the answer to the question.
</p>

